paragraphs.title: derive additional features and drop unnecessary fields
paragraphs.text:
%script
--drop undesired columns, extract year,quarter, building age, and cast ResidFar and CT2010 as numbers
begin execute immediate 'drop table brooklyn_v1'; exception when others then null; end;
/
CREATE table brooklyn_v1 AS 
    (SELECT 
    record_no as transaction_id, building_class_category, gross_sqft, building_class_at_sale, sale_price, sale_date,
    to_char(extract(year from to_date(sale_date, 'YYYY-MM-DD'))) as year_str, 
    to_char(to_date(sale_date, 'YYYY-MM-DD'), 'Q') as quarter,
    address_, YearBuilt,
    extract(year from to_date(sale_date, 'YYYY-MM-DD')) -  to_number(YearBuilt) as Age_years,
    to_number(ResidFar) as ResidFar,
    case 
        when (CT2010 = 'NA') then 0 
        else to_number(CT2010) end 
        as CT2010,
    SchoolDist, SanitDistr, NumFloors, AssessTot, XCoord, YCoord, LAND_SQFT, AssessLand, LotFront, SHAPE_Leng
    FROM admin.brooklyn_sales_raw
    where (to_number(YearBuilt) >= 1800));
    
select count(*) from brooklyn_v1;

%python
#compare 1-2 family homes to rental properties
query = """
    select transaction_id, sale_price, XCOORD, YCOORD, building_class_category from brooklyn_v1 where (XCOORD > 0) and (YCOORD > 0) and (SALE_PRICE > 1.0)
"""
df = oml.sync(query=query).pull()
idx = (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '02 TWO FAMILY HOMES') | (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '01 ONE FAMILY HOMES')
df.loc[idx, 'multi_family'] = '1-2'
idx = (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '10  COOPS - ELEVATOR APARTMENTS') | (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '03 THREE FAMILY HOMES') \
    | (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '07  RENTALS - WALKUP APARTMENTS')  | (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '09  COOPS - WALKUP APARTMENTS') \
    | (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY == '14  RENTALS - 4-10 UNIT')
df.loc[idx, 'multi_family'] = 'rentals'
print (df.BUILDING_CLASS_CATEGORY.value_counts().head(12))
print (df.multi_family.value_counts())

paragraphs.title: preserve one & two family homes ie drop rentals and commercial properties
drop edge cases ie keep 53K records having typical sale_price, gross_sqft, and YearBuilt
paragraphs.text:
%script
--preserve records having $250K < sale_price < $3M and 700 < gross_sqft < 5000 and 1900 <= YearBuilt <=2010
--and BUILDING_CLASS_AT_SALE having A1,A5 (single family homes) or B1-B3 (two family)
--and add a column of random numbers
begin execute immediate 'drop table BROOKLYN_V3'; exception when others then null; end;
/
create table BROOKLYN_V3 as 
    select B.*, dbms_random.value(0.0, 1.0) as ran_num from BROOKLYN_V2 B 
    where (sale_price >= 2.5e5) and (sale_price <= 3.0e6)
    and   (gross_sqft >= 700  ) and (gross_sqft <= 5000 )
    and (YearBuilt >= 1900) and (YearBuilt <= 2010)
    and (BUILDING_CLASS_AT_SALE in ('A1', 'A5', 'B1', 'B2', 'B3'))
    ;
select count(*) from brooklyn_v3;

paragraphs.title: use python to compute feature importance
paragraphs.text:
%python
#this could also be done via PL/SQL
train = oml.sync(table='BROOKLYN_TRAIN')
x = train.drop(target)
y = train[target]
print ('x.shape, y.shape = ', x.shape, y.shape)
setting = {'ODMS_SAMPLING':'ODMS_SAMPLING_DISABLE'}
feature_importance_model = oml.ai(**setting)
feature_importance_model = feature_importance_model.fit(x, y, case_id=case_id)
df = feature_importance_model.importance.pull()
df.importance = df.importance/df.importance.sum()
feature_importance = df
feature_importance.head()
